{"timestamp":"2026-07-18T13:24:41.643Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"agent_reasoning","text":"**Clarifying benchmark differences and token counting**"}}
{"timestamp":"2026-07-18T13:24:41.649Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"id":"rs_0bd6d73b974b1fab016a5b7e99a06c8191860487426b7b4a78","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7564-f8e8-7981-b0a9-28667898c518"},"summary":[{"text":"**Clarifying benchmark differences and token counting**","type":"summary_text"}],"type":"reasoning"}}
{"timestamp":"2026-07-18T13:24:41.662Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"agent_message","message":"They aren’t generally faster or more token-effective. The three-repository aggregate made it look that way because it mixed a narrow grep-friendly workload, cold-start overhead, and one genuine Entire Graph failure on Zod.\n\nThe actual aggregate was:\n\n| Metric | File tools | Entire Graph |\n|---|---:|---:|\n| Exact pass rate | 0.667 | 0.667 |\n| Recall | 1.000 | 1.000 |\n| Provider input tokens, including cache | 371,759 | **286,523** |\n| Tool calls | 10.7 | **10.3** |\n| Output tokens | **14,581** | 19,989 |\n| Mean time | **82.6s** | 94.3s |\n| Cost | **$0.962** | $1.136 |\n\nSo Entire Graph used **23% fewer input tokens** and slightly fewer calls, with identical recorded quality. File tools won latency, generated-output tokens, and therefore cost.\n\nWhy the apparent reversal:\n\n- “File tools” were not reading the entire repository. Claude used targeted `Grep`, `Glob`, and `Read`. These smoke questions used distinctive symbol names and shallow compiler-derived neighborhoods—the ideal case for grep.\n- Each treatment ran in isolation with cold caches. Entire Graph paid parsing/index startup costs without getting the benefit of multiple queries over the same index.\n- Zod dominated the difference. At the tested Graph head, `neighbors` returned only 1 of 7 callers and omitted the abstract declaration. Claude then had to use Entire Graph **and** manually reconstruct the missing results with file tools: 19 calls, 198.6s, and $0.727 versus file tools’ 15 calls, 155.7s, and $0.523.\n- On the other two repositories, Entire Graph behaved much more like the earlier results:\n  - Chi: 5 versus 7 calls and $0.181 versus $0.219, though about 5 seconds slower.\n  - Click: 7 versus 10 calls and **49s versus 62s**, with nearly equal cost.\n- This was one attempt per treatment per repository. That is enough to expose pipeline/product defects, but not enough to establish a stable latency ranking.\n- The exactness score also contains oracle-scope penalties: both systems returned a valid abstract TypeScript declaration and a valid Python construction site that the oracle excluded. Thus the 0.667 tie understates both.\n\nMost importantly, the paid smoke tested Entire Graph at `8a647f0`. The Zod relationship repair now in PR #43 at `0244ef1` was made afterward and has passed the full test suite and CI, but it has **not** been rerun in the paid agent comparison. We therefore cannot claim the repaired version now wins.\n\nThe honest conclusion is: the earlier token-efficiency result remains visible—Graph reduced model input substantially. The smoke exposed that cold, one-symbol grep workloads can favor native file tools, and that the tested Graph version had a real TypeScript neighborhood gap which erased its normal advantage. The aggregate was not evidence that scanning files is intrinsically more efficient than Graph. [Diagnostic report](/private/tmp/brain-bench-graph-agentic-pilot/competitive-eval/oracle-agentic-overlay/diagnostic-run-20260718.md)","phase":"final_answer","memory_citation":null}}
{"timestamp":"2026-07-18T13:24:41.662Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","id":"msg_0bd6d73b974b1fab016a5b7e99a2308191a95d5aec22b1cdd1","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"output_text","text":"They aren’t generally faster or more token-effective. The three-repository aggregate made it look that way because it mixed a narrow grep-friendly workload, cold-start overhead, and one genuine Entire Graph failure on Zod.\n\nThe actual aggregate was:\n\n| Metric | File tools | Entire Graph |\n|---|---:|---:|\n| Exact pass rate | 0.667 | 0.667 |\n| Recall | 1.000 | 1.000 |\n| Provider input tokens, including cache | 371,759 | **286,523** |\n| Tool calls | 10.7 | **10.3** |\n| Output tokens | **14,581** | 19,989 |\n| Mean time | **82.6s** | 94.3s |\n| Cost | **$0.962** | $1.136 |\n\nSo Entire Graph used **23% fewer input tokens** and slightly fewer calls, with identical recorded quality. File tools won latency, generated-output tokens, and therefore cost.\n\nWhy the apparent reversal:\n\n- “File tools” were not reading the entire repository. Claude used targeted `Grep`, `Glob`, and `Read`. These smoke questions used distinctive symbol names and shallow compiler-derived neighborhoods—the ideal case for grep.\n- Each treatment ran in isolation with cold caches. Entire Graph paid parsing/index startup costs without getting the benefit of multiple queries over the same index.\n- Zod dominated the difference. At the tested Graph head, `neighbors` returned only 1 of 7 callers and omitted the abstract declaration. Claude then had to use Entire Graph **and** manually reconstruct the missing results with file tools: 19 calls, 198.6s, and $0.727 versus file tools’ 15 calls, 155.7s, and $0.523.\n- On the other two repositories, Entire Graph behaved much more like the earlier results:\n  - Chi: 5 versus 7 calls and $0.181 versus $0.219, though about 5 seconds slower.\n  - Click: 7 versus 10 calls and **49s versus 62s**, with nearly equal cost.\n- This was one attempt per treatment per repository. That is enough to expose pipeline/product defects, but not enough to establish a stable latency ranking.\n- The exactness score also contains oracle-scope penalties: both systems returned a valid abstract TypeScript declaration and a valid Python construction site that the oracle excluded. Thus the 0.667 tie understates both.\n\nMost importantly, the paid smoke tested Entire Graph at `8a647f0`. The Zod relationship repair now in PR #43 at `0244ef1` was made afterward and has passed the full test suite and CI, but it has **not** been rerun in the paid agent comparison. We therefore cannot claim the repaired version now wins.\n\nThe honest conclusion is: the earlier token-efficiency result remains visible—Graph reduced model input substantially. The smoke exposed that cold, one-symbol grep workloads can favor native file tools, and that the tested Graph version had a real TypeScript neighborhood gap which erased its normal advantage. The aggregate was not evidence that scanning files is intrinsically more efficient than Graph. [Diagnostic report](/private/tmp/brain-bench-graph-agentic-pilot/competitive-eval/oracle-agentic-overlay/diagnostic-run-20260718.md)"}],"phase":"final_answer","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7564-f8e8-7981-b0a9-28667898c518"}}}
